    summary: "Office-backed CMBS delinquency set a fresh all-time high above 12% in early 2026 even as vacancy finally turned the corner, while data centers and industrial remain the structurally favored sectors pulling capital toward the opposite end of the risk barbell.",
    keyPoints: [
      "Office CMBS delinquency hit 12.34% in January 2026, a record, driven by large maturity defaults including Worldwide Plaza ($940M) and One New York Plaza ($835M), per Trepp",
      "Overall Trepp CMBS delinquency rate rose 41bps to 7.55% in March 2026, reversing February's decline",
      "National office vacancy peaked at 20.7% in Q2 2025 (highest on record) but fell to 17.6% by April 2026, down ~210bps year-over-year",
      "Office construction is set to hit a 25-year low in 2026, which forecasters expect to pull vacancy toward 15.9% by year-end",
      "North American data center vacancy held at a record ~1% in 2025 with rents up 9% and 92% of capacity under construction already pre-committed (JLL)",
      "Industrial transaction volume surged 54.4% in 2025 to $44.9B, the strongest growth of any major property type (MSCI RCA)",
    ],
    body: [
      "The standing story in US commercial real estate is divergence, not recovery. The office sector posted its worst-ever credit reading in early 2026: Trepp's office CMBS delinquency rate reached 12.34% in January, surpassing prior records and exceeding Global Financial Crisis levels. The spike was concentrated rather than broad, driven by a handful of marquee Manhattan loans hitting maturity defaults, notably Worldwide Plaza at roughly $940M and One New York Plaza at $835M. The all-property Trepp delinquency rate climbed 41 basis points to 7.55% in March 2026, showing that the refinancing wall is still being worked through rather than behind the market.",
      "Yet the operating fundamentals are quietly healing even as the legacy debt detonates. The national office vacancy rate peaked at 20.7% in Q2 2025, the highest on record and above the Savings and Loan crisis high, then fell to 17.6% by April 2026, roughly 210 basis points lower year-over-year. The mechanism is supply starvation: office construction is projected to hit a 25-year low in 2026, which combined with modest demand gains has some forecasters modeling vacancy near 15.9% by year-end. The catch is bifurcation. CBRE expects the gap between newer prime space and older secondary stock to widen further, so a single national vacancy number masks a market where trophy assets lease and commodity towers face the wrecking ball or conversion.",
      "On the other end of the barbell, data centers remain the asset class capital chases hardest. North American vacancy held at roughly 1% for a second consecutive year in 2025 despite record construction, per JLL, with CBRE earlier in 2025 citing an all-time low of 1.6%. Rents rose 9% in 2025, in line with the 10% five-year CAGR, and listings above 1 MW commanded premium increases of 13%. The pre-leasing tells the scarcity story: 92% of capacity under construction is already committed via binding leases or owner-occupied builds, leaving almost nothing speculative for latecomers. Industrial rounds out the strong end, with 2025 transaction volume up 54.4% to $44.9B, the fastest growth of any major sector in the MSCI RCA data. For allocators, the message is that the office distress headlines and the data center gold rush are two ends of one repricing, not contradictory signals.",
    ],
